#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:1
msgid "E0009"
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:3
msgid "Warning name: `struct_never_constructed`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:5
msgid "The struct is never constructed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:7
msgid "Erroneous example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:9
msgid ""
"///|\n"
"pub struct A { // Warning: the struct A is never constructed\n"
"  value : Int\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"///|\n"
"priv struct B { // Warning: the struct B is never constructed\n"
"  value : Int\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"///|\n"
"fn B::get(a : B) -> Int {\n"
"  a.value\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:13
msgid "Suggestion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:15
msgid ""
"The `pub` visibility modifier only allows other packages to access the "
"struct, by dot-syntax (`a.value`), or by pattern matching. Therefore, if "
"you expect other packages to be able to construct the struct, you should "
"use the `pub(all)` visibility modifier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:20
msgid ""
"\n"
"///|\n"
"pub(all) struct A {\n"
"  value : Int\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:26
msgid ""
"However, if you do not want other packages to construct the struct, this "
"might be due to incompleteness or bugs in your code. There are some "
"common cases:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:29
msgid ""
"You planned to use smart constructors or factory functions to construct "
"the struct, but you forgot or have not implemented them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:31
msgid ""
"You intended to keep the struct private to control its instantiation but "
"may have forgotten to provide a way to do so within its own package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:34
msgid ""
"In these cases, you should consider providing a way to construct the "
"struct within its own package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../language/error_codes/E0009.md:37
msgid ""
"\n"
"///|\n"
"priv struct B {\n"
"  value : Int\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"///|\n"
"fn B::new(value : Int) -> B {\n"
"  B::{ value, }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

